"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkwebsite=globalThis.webpackChunkwebsite||[]).push([[4001],{8883(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"if-else","metadata":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/if-else","editUrl":"https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/tree/main/docs/website/blog/2026-05-07-if-else.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-07-if-else.md","title":"Functions defined piecewise","description":"Gradgen v0.5.2","date":"2026-05-07T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"New version","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/tags/new_version","description":"Release of new version"}],"readingTime":0.48,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Pantelis Sopasakis","title":"Lecturer, QUB","url":"https://github.com/alphaville","page":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/authors/pantelis"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/alphaville","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/sopasakis/"},"imageURL":"https://www.qub.ac.uk/schools/media/Media1218037smxx.png","key":"pantelis"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"if-else","title":"Functions defined piecewise","authors":["pantelis"],"tags":["release"],"description":"Gradgen v0.5.2","keywords":["gradgen","Rust code generation","Piecewise functions"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Gradgen v0.5.1 brings new features and improvements","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/v0.5.1"}},"content":"[Gradgen v0.5.2](https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/releases/tag/v0.5.2) brings functions defined piecewise using [`if_else`](/gradgen/docs/basics/symbolic#expressions-defined-piecewise). Moreover, gradgen allows the differentiation of these functions. \\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nThe user can define symbolic expressions of the following form\\n\\n$$f = \\\\begin{cases}\\nf_1, & \\\\text{ if } (\\\\text{condition})\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nf_2, & \\\\text{ otherwise}\\n\\\\end{cases}$$\\n\\nFor example, the Heaviside functions with parameters $p$, that is \\n$f(x) = 0$ if $x < p$ and $f(x) = 1$ if $x \\\\geq p$ is defined as \\n\\n```python\\nx = SX.sym(\\"x\\")\\np = SX.sym(\\"p\\")\\nf = if_else(0, 1, x < p)\\n```"},{"id":"v0.5.1","metadata":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/v0.5.1","editUrl":"https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/tree/main/docs/website/blog/2026-05-06-v0.5.1.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-06-v0.5.1.md","title":"Gradgen v0.5.1 brings new features and improvements","description":"Gradgen v0.5.1 introduces a bunch of new functionality and performance improvements from second-order cones to efficient memory allocation","date":"2026-05-06T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"New version","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/tags/new_version","description":"Release of new version"}],"readingTime":0.66,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Pantelis Sopasakis","title":"Lecturer, QUB","url":"https://github.com/alphaville","page":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/authors/pantelis"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/alphaville","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/sopasakis/"},"imageURL":"https://www.qub.ac.uk/schools/media/Media1218037smxx.png","key":"pantelis"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"v0.5.1","title":"Gradgen v0.5.1 brings new features and improvements","authors":["pantelis"],"tags":["release"],"description":"Gradgen v0.5.1 introduces a bunch of new functionality and performance improvements from second-order cones to efficient memory allocation","keywords":["gradgen","Rust code generation","second-order cone","SOC"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Functions defined piecewise","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/if-else"},"nextItem":{"title":"What\'s new in v0.5.0","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/v0.5.0"}},"content":"[Gradgen v0.5.1](https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/releases/tag/v0.5.1) brings second-order cones (SOCs), which are useful in convex optimization. It also brings significant improvements in the generated code leading to a more \\"economic\\" allocation of workspace memory. Earlier, workspace would almost always be required, whereas now we check whether the output variable can serve as workspace. More thorough unit testing is also done (we now have 538 unit tests running on GitHub Actions). This includes integration tests where we compare the results obtained by gradgen to [`sympy`](https://www.sympy.org/en/index.html).\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nGradgen v0.5.1 can be installed using `pip`:\\n\\n```bash\\npip install gradgen==0.5.1\\n```\\n\\nUpcoming developments:\\n- Improved documentation and examples, including Python notebooks on Google Colab and demos\\n- Benchmarks\\n- Support for the forward-backward envelope in optimal control problems"},{"id":"v0.5.0","metadata":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/v0.5.0","editUrl":"https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/tree/main/docs/website/blog/2026-05-02-v0.5.0.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-05-02-v0.5.0.md","title":"What\'s new in v0.5.0","description":"Gradgen v0.5.0 adds embeddable Rust code generation improvements, shorter OCP-generated code, and better support for OpEn integration.","date":"2026-05-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"New version","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/tags/new_version","description":"Release of new version"}],"readingTime":0.58,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Pantelis Sopasakis","title":"Lecturer, QUB","url":"https://github.com/alphaville","page":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/authors/pantelis"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/alphaville","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/sopasakis/"},"imageURL":"https://www.qub.ac.uk/schools/media/Media1218037smxx.png","key":"pantelis"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"v0.5.0","title":"What\'s new in v0.5.0","authors":["pantelis"],"tags":["release"],"description":"Gradgen v0.5.0 adds embeddable Rust code generation improvements, shorter OCP-generated code, and better support for OpEn integration.","keywords":["gradgen","rust code generation","automatic differentiation","no_std","optimal control"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Gradgen v0.5.1 brings new features and improvements","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/v0.5.1"},"nextItem":{"title":"API docs","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/api-docs"}},"content":"[Gradgen v0.5.0](https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/releases/tag/v0.5.0) brings significant changes and new functionality. \\nMost importantly, it brings us very close to a full integration \\nwith [OpEn](https://alphaville.github.io/optimization-engine/),\\nthis means that:\\n- We\'ll be generating pure Rust code, fully embeddable (`#[no-std]`),\\n  safe, with support for both single and double precision arithmetic\\n- The generated code for optimal control problems will be significantly shorter.\\n  This will decrease significantly the compilation times (from minutes to seconds)\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nGradgen v0.5.0 can be installed using `pip`:\\n\\n```bash\\npip install gradgen==0.5.0\\n```\\n\\nUpcoming developments:\\n- Improved documentation and examples, including Python notebooks on Google Colab and demos\\n- Benchmarks\\n- Support for the forward-backward envelope in optimal control problems"},{"id":"api-docs","metadata":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/api-docs","editUrl":"https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/tree/main/docs/website/blog/2026-04-30-api-docs.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-30-api-docs.md","title":"API docs","description":"The API docs of gradgen are now available here. The API docs have been generated automatically from the docstrings in the code using Sphinx.","date":"2026-04-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"New version","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/tags/new_version","description":"Release of new version"}],"readingTime":0.63,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Pantelis Sopasakis","title":"Lecturer, QUB","url":"https://github.com/alphaville","page":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/authors/pantelis"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/alphaville","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/sopasakis/"},"imageURL":"https://www.qub.ac.uk/schools/media/Media1218037smxx.png","key":"pantelis"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"api-docs","title":"API docs","authors":["pantelis"],"tags":["release"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"What\'s new in v0.5.0","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/v0.5.0"},"nextItem":{"title":"Gradgen revival","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/first-blog-post"}},"content":"The API docs of gradgen are now available [here](https://qub-asl.github.io/gradgen/api-dox/). The API docs have been generated automatically from the docstrings in the code using [Sphinx](https://www.sphinx-doc.org/en/master/).\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nFor example, you can find detailed API docs for the [`SingleShootingBundle`](https://qub-asl.github.io/gradgen/api-dox/api/gradgen.html#module-gradgen.single_shooting) class, [`SquaredDistanceToSet`](https://qub-asl.github.io/gradgen/api-dox/api/gradgen.html#gradgen.squared_distance_to_set.SquaredDistanceToSet) and a lot more. \\n\\nThe API docs are still under development. Currently, the majority of public API endpoints (classes, methods, functions) have API docs. The next step will be to include examples and code snippets everywhere.\\n\\nNote that best way to get started with gradgen is our [online documentation](/gradgen/docs/category/learn), not the API docs."},{"id":"first-blog-post","metadata":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/first-blog-post","editUrl":"https://github.com/QUB-ASL/gradgen/tree/main/docs/website/blog/2026-03-31-first-blog-post.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-31-first-blog-post.md","title":"Gradgen revival","description":"Welcome to this brand new website of gradgen: your Python module for automatic differentiation and truly embedded Rust code generation.","date":"2026-03-31T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":false,"label":"New version","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/tags/new_version","description":"Release of new version"}],"readingTime":0.65,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Pantelis Sopasakis","title":"Lecturer, QUB","url":"https://github.com/alphaville","page":{"permalink":"/gradgen/blog/authors/pantelis"},"socials":{"github":"https://github.com/alphaville","linkedin":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/sopasakis/"},"imageURL":"https://www.qub.ac.uk/schools/media/Media1218037smxx.png","key":"pantelis"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"first-blog-post","title":"Gradgen revival","authors":["pantelis"],"tags":["release"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"API docs","permalink":"/gradgen/blog/api-docs"}},"content":"Welcome to this brand new website of gradgen: your Python module for automatic differentiation and truly embedded Rust code generation.\\n\\nGradgen v0.3 brings two significant changes:\\n\\n1. It has been redesigned to generate **Rust crates**, optionally marked with `#[no_std]` so you can use them directly in your embedded applications\\n2. It comes with specialised code generation mechanisms for **optimal control** leading to Rust code that **does not increase in size** with the prediction horizon\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\nWe are already working on gradgen v0.3 which will bring one more significant change: support for high-order functions like **map**, **zip**, and **reduce**, which will improve code generation even more. \\n\\nOur goal is to exploit the structure of a function, its gradient, and Hessian to generate more efficient, elegant, and fast Rust code."}]}}')}}]);